  "name": "Extract Technical API Constraints for Legal Exhibits",
  "summary": "Analyzes developer documentation\u2014primarily OpenAPI/Swagger specifications, plus narrative docs\u2014to extract rate limits, authentication methods, data fields, and other technical constraints for inclusion in legal exhibits and contract schedules. Produces a structured, traceable API Access & Constraints Schedule with defined terms, risk flags, and change-management provisions, bridging the gap between engineering artifacts and legally precise contract language.",
  "content": "# Extract Technical API Constraints for Legal Exhibits\n\n**Slug**: `extract-technical-api-constraints`\n**Version**: 1.0\n\n---\n\n## Assumptions Used\n\nUnless overridden at Checkpoint A, this skill proceeds on these defaults:\n\n1. **Use case**: Drafting an **API Access & Constraints Schedule** to attach to an MSA/SOW for a B2B SaaS/API provider.\n2. **API protocol**: RESTful API documented via **OpenAPI Specification (OAS) v3.0+** (or Swagger v2.0). Non-RESTful APIs (GraphQL, gRPC) may require adaptation of extraction patterns.\n3. **Commitment posture**: The exhibit is **primarily descriptive** (documents current technical behavior) and avoids creating new warranties unless explicitly requested.\n4. **Contract posture**: **Outbound** (you are the API provider). Alternatives: Inbound (you are the client) or Mutual Integration.\n5. **Scope**: Single API product, **one production environment** plus sandbox (if referenced), current GA version.\n6. **Audience**: Commercial counsel / legal ops with access to engineering for confirmation.\n\n> **Important**: Document all deviations from these assumptions in the Risk/Gap Log.\n\n## Open Items / Needed Inputs\n\nProvide if available; if not, the workflow still produces a draft with flagged gaps:\n\n- Agreement type and label: Exhibit/Schedule name, and whether it is customer paper or vendor paper.\n- Governing law and any regulated-industry constraints (health, financial services, education).\n- API sources: OpenAPI file(s), developer portal URLs, auth docs, rate limit/quotas page, SLA/support policy pages.\n- Scope boundaries: which endpoints are in-scope, versions, regions, environments (prod/sandbox), and whether webhooks are included.\n- Data classification guidance: what counts as Personal Data, Sensitive Personal Data, PHI, PCI, secrets.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 0: Minimum-Input Alignment (MANDATORY)\n\n### Checkpoint A: Pre-Draft Intake Snapshot\n\nConfirm these parameters before extraction begins. Defaults shown in **bold**. If you do not respond, the skill proceeds using defaults and flags uncertainties.\n\n| # | Parameter | Default | Alternatives |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Exhibit type / placement** | **MSA/SOW Exhibit: \"API Access & Constraints Schedule\"** | DPA Annex; Security Exhibit; Order Form attachment |\n| 2 | **API scope** | **Single API, current GA version** | Multiple APIs; include beta endpoints; include webhooks; include partner-only endpoints |\n| 3 | **Contract posture** | **Outbound (Provider)** | Inbound (Client); Mutual Integration |\n| 4 | **Commitment level** | **Descriptive / as-is** | Binding commitments; Hybrid (commit to specific SLOs and notice periods only) |\n| 5 | **Constraint categories** | **Auth + rate limits + data fields** | Add: environments, IP allowlisting, logging/audit, error handling, deprecation policy, SLA/SLO references, sub-processors for data flows |\n| 6 | **Output mode** | **Full Package** | Quick Reference; Checklist Only; Risk Matrix |\n\n**Assumptions explicitly made if unanswered**: Use the bold defaults above.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1: Source Intake, Normalization & Taxonomy Mapping\n\n### Objective\n\nCreate a defensible \"evidence set\" of technical sources, normalize them into an extraction-ready format, and map technical documentation fields to their legal significance.\n\n### Deliverables\n\n1. **Source Register** (table)\n2. **Normalized Spec Notes** (short bullet digest of versions, servers, auth schemes, tags)\n3. **Technical-to-Legal Crosswalk** (table)\n\n### Steps\n\n- Collect sources (priority order):\n  1. OpenAPI/Swagger JSON/YAML (including component schemas)\n  2. Auth guide (OAuth/API keys/JWT/mTLS)\n  3. Rate limit/quotas documentation\n  4. Changelog / deprecation policy / breaking-changes policy (often in READMEs)\n  5. Error code documentation\n  6. Data model docs and examples\n  7. SLA/support policy pages (if you will reference uptime/support in the exhibit)\n- Lock the versions and timestamps.\n- Normalize:\n  - Convert OpenAPI to a stable view (rendered HTML or parsed tables) and record the spec version.\n  - Capture server URLs and environment labels (prod/sandbox/regional).\n  - Identify security schemes under `components.securitySchemes` and global vs. operation-level security.\n\n### Template: Source Register\n\n| ID | Source Type | URL / File | Version / Commit | Retrieved (UTC) | Owner | Notes / Reliability |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| S-1 | OpenAPI spec | | | | Eng | Primary / authoritative |\n| S-2 | Auth docs | | | | Eng | |\n| S-3 | Rate limit docs | | | | Eng/Support | May differ by plan |\n| S-4 | Changelog / deprecation | | | | PM | |\n| S-5 | Error code docs | | | | Eng | |\n\n### Template: Technical-to-Legal Crosswalk\n\n| OpenAPI Field / Doc Section | Example Value | Legal Significance | Typical Clause Reference |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `info.version` | v2.1.0 | Versioning & Sunset Rights | Maintenance & Support; Change Mgmt |\n| `servers[].url` | `https://api.example.com` | Data Residency / Jurisdiction | Privacy & Compliance; Exhibit \u00a71 |\n| `paths.{path}.{method}` | GET /v1/widgets | Scope of License / Permitted Actions | Grant of License; Exhibit \u00a74 |\n| `components.securitySchemes` | OAuth2 (client_credentials) | Security Standards / Liability | Security & Indemnity; Exhibit \u00a72 |\n| `x-ratelimit-limit` (or docs) | 1000/min | Usage Caps / Overages / SLA | Fees / Service Levels; Exhibit \u00a73 |\n| `components.schemas.{Model}` | User { email, ssn } | PII / Regulated Data | DPA; Data Processing Schedule |\n\n### Checklist (Phase 1)\n\n- [ ] Identify authoritative source hierarchy (spec vs. portal vs. blog post)\n- [ ] Record retrieval date/time for each source\n- [ ] Confirm API versioning scheme (path-based `/v1/`, header-based, query-based)\n- [ ] Capture environment base URLs and any region-specific endpoints\n- [ ] Note if spec includes `x-` vendor extensions relevant to limits/auth\n- [ ] Map each key technical field to its legal clause reference\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Technical Constraint Extraction (Auth, Rate Limits, Data Model, Operations)\n\n### Objective\n\nExtract the technical constraints most likely to become legally relevant statements.\n\n### Deliverables\n\n1. **API Constraint Extraction Table** (endpoint-by-endpoint)\n2. **Data Field Inventory** (schemas \u2192 fields, requiredness, sensitivity flags)\n3. **Auth & Access Profile** (methods, token lifetimes, scopes)\n4. **Rate Limit Profile** (requests/time, burst, quotas, headers, 429 behavior)\n\n### Extraction Framework\n\n#### A. Authentication & Authorization\n\n- Scheme(s): API key, OAuth2 (authorization code / client credentials), JWT bearer, mTLS, HMAC signatures.\n- Credential placement: header / query / cookie.\n- Scope model: OAuth scopes, RBAC roles, tenant isolation.\n- Token lifecycle: expiration, refresh, rotation expectations.\n- IP allowlisting / network controls (if documented).\n\n#### B. Rate Limits / Quotas\n\n- Hard limits (per minute/hour/day), burst limits.\n- Dimensions: per API key, per tenant, per IP, per endpoint group.\n- Limit headers: `X-RateLimit-Limit`, `X-RateLimit-Remaining`, `Retry-After`.\n- Enforcement behavior: HTTP 429; backoff requirements; throttling vs. blocking.\n- Tiering: limits vary by plan/order form.\n- **Legal mapping**: How does a 429 event relate to \"Suspension of Service\" rights or SLA exclusions?\n\n#### C. Endpoints / Operations\n\nFor each operation (method + path):\n- Required request fields and formats.\n- Idempotency requirements (idempotency keys).\n- Pagination / filters / sorting constraints.\n- Max payload size.\n- Async operations and webhooks (delivery retries, signing, event schemas).\n\n#### D. Data Fields (Legally Salient)\n\n- Personal Data fields (names, emails, identifiers) and Sensitive categories.\n- Authentication secrets and tokens.\n- Financial / health / education identifiers (PCI, PHI, FERPA).\n- Data minimization: required vs. optional fields.\n- Data residency hints (region-specific servers).\n\n#### E. Error Handling & Reliability Signals\n\n- Standard error object schema.\n- Retriable vs. non-retriable codes.\n- **Impact on SLA**: Which error codes (4xx vs. 5xx) count toward or are excluded from uptime calculations?\n- Deprecation headers, sunset policies (if present).\n\n### Template: API Constraint Extraction Table\n\n| Tag / Domain | Method | Path | Summary | Auth Required? | Auth Type / Scopes | Rate Limit (doc) | Key Request Fields (required) | Key Response Fields | Pagination / Max | Errors (notable) | Notes / Legal Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| | GET | /v1/widgets | List widgets | Yes | OAuth2: widgets:read | 60 rpm (per key) | tenant_id | items[].id, items[].status | limit<=100 | 401/403/429 | Rate limit should not be warranted unless committed |\n\n### Template: Data Field Inventory\n\n| Schema | Field | Type | Required? | Example | Likely Classification | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| User | email | string | Yes | a@b.com | Personal Data | Consider DPA mapping |\n| Payment | card_last4 | string | No | 1234 | PCI-related | Avoid storing full PAN |\n| User | ip_address | string | No | 192.168.1.1 | Personal Data (GDPR) | Log retention implications |\n\n### Checklist (Phase 2)\n\n- [ ] Identify all `securitySchemes` and map to operations (global + per-operation)\n- [ ] Extract OAuth scopes and ensure they align with exhibit terms (\"least privilege\")\n- [ ] Locate rate limit statements (spec extensions, docs pages, response headers)\n- [ ] Extract \"required\" fields from request bodies and path/query parameters\n- [ ] Flag any fields likely to be regulated/sensitive\n- [ ] Note any contradictions between spec and narrative docs\n- [ ] Map HTTP error codes to potential legal consequences (SLA exclusions, suspension rights)\n\n> **Tip**: Treat rate limits and field definitions as **time-sensitive**; build the exhibit to allow updates via change-control rather than hard-wiring guarantees.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3: Legal Translation & Exhibit Drafting\n\n### Objective\n\nConvert extracted technical constraints into contract-ready exhibit language that is accurate, non-ambiguous, and appropriately bounded.\n\n### Deliverables\n\n1. **API Access & Constraints Schedule** (draft exhibit)\n2. **Defined Terms & Interpretive Notes** (embedded or appendix)\n\n### Drafting Principles\n\n- **Do not over-warrant** undocumented behavior. Prefer \"as described in Documentation as of [date]\" paired with notice/change control.\n- **Separate descriptive from committed**: If you must commit, use measurable metrics and tie them to plan/tier.\n- **Bind to artifacts**: \"Documentation\" definition includes specific URLs/files (Source Register IDs).\n- **Control updates**: Add a \"Documentation Updates\" clause and \"material adverse change\" concept if customer requires.\n- **Avoid silent scope creep**: Define \"API\" by name, version, and base URL(s).\n- **Map errors to rights**: Explicitly state which error conditions (e.g., 429) constitute permissible suspension vs. SLA failures.\n\n### Exhibit Template: API Access & Constraints Schedule\n\n---\n\n**EXHIBIT [___]: API ACCESS & CONSTRAINTS SCHEDULE**\n\n**Effective Date**: [___]\n\n#### Section 1. API Identification\n\n- **API Name**: [Product / API name]\n- **API Version(s)**: [v1 / 2026-01]\n- **Base URLs / Environments**:\n  - Production: [https://api.example.com]\n  - Sandbox/Test (if any): [https://sandbox-api.example.com]\n- **Documentation**: The documentation sources listed in the **Source Register** (IDs: [S-1\u2026S-n]) as retrieved on [date] (the \"**Documentation**\").\n\n#### Section 2. Authentication and Access Controls\n\n- **Supported Authentication Methods**: [OAuth 2.0 Client Credentials / API Key / mTLS].\n- **Credential Placement**: [Authorization header: Bearer \\<token\\>].\n- **Scopes / Roles**: [List scopes/roles or reference table].\n- **Tenant Isolation**: Access is logically segregated by [tenant/account identifier] as described in Documentation.\n- **Client Obligations**: Client is solely responsible for the security, rotation, and confidentiality of all credentials issued to Client.\n- **Security Notes** (optional): [IP allowlisting requirements, key rotation guidance, webhook signature verification].\n\n*Optional commitment language (use only if approved):*\n> Provider will maintain the authentication method(s) listed above for the then-current GA version of the API, subject to Section 6 (Change Management).\n\n#### Section 3. Rate Limits / Quotas / Throttling\n\n- **Published Limits**: [Insert specific limits if stable and tier-bound; otherwise reference Documentation].\n- **Limit Dimensions**: [per API key / per tenant / per IP / per endpoint group].\n- **Burst Tolerance**: [Allowed / Not documented / Up to X requests in Y-second window].\n- **Throttle Response**: Requests exceeding limits may receive **HTTP 429 Too Many Requests** and/or other responses as described in Documentation. Client will implement reasonable exponential backoff.\n- **Relationship to SLA**: Rate-limit throttling (HTTP 429) [does / does not] constitute Downtime for purposes of the SLA. Provider-initiated throttling for abuse or security purposes is excluded from SLA calculations.\n\n*Safer descriptive phrasing:*\n> Rate limits may vary by service plan, endpoint, and system conditions and are described in the Documentation.\n\n#### Section 4. Endpoint Scope and Core Operations\n\nThe \"**API Services**\" consist of the endpoints listed below [or: defined in the OpenAPI specification attached as Exhibit [___]-A].\n\n| Operation | Purpose | Auth / Scopes | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| GET /v1/widgets | List widgets | widgets:read | Pagination limit 100 |\n| POST /v1/widgets | Create widget | widgets:write | Idempotency key required |\n\nEndpoints marked \"beta,\" \"experimental,\" or \"preview\" in the Documentation are expressly excluded from the scope of this Schedule and from any service-level commitments.\n\n#### Section 5. Data Fields and Data Handling Notes\n\n- **Primary Objects**: [Widget, User, Event].\n- **Required Fields (by operation/object)**: [Reference Data Field Inventory or attach as sub-schedule].\n- **Sensitive Data**: The API is **not intended** to process [PHI / PCI / Special Category Data] except as expressly documented and authorized. Client shall not submit such data unless the parties have executed a [BAA / PCI Addendum / appropriate supplement].\n- **Webhooks** (if any): Event payload schemas, delivery retry policies, and signing/verification requirements are as described in Documentation.\n\n> See @privacy-and-security-exhibit-builder for expanded PII mapping and DPA cross-referencing.\n\n#### Section 6. Change Management / Versioning / Deprecation\n\n- **Versioning**: [path-based / header-based] as described in Documentation.\n- **Breaking Changes**: Provider defines a \"Breaking Change\" as [removal of an endpoint, removal of a required response field, change to authentication method, or change to error response format].\n- **Deprecation Notice**: Provider will use commercially reasonable efforts to provide [X] days' notice before implementing Breaking Changes to GA endpoints, via [changelog / email / Deprecation header].\n- **Material Changes** (optional negotiated term): [X] days' prior written notice for changes that materially reduce functionality or materially increase Client's integration burden.\n\n> See @contract-change-management-and-versioning for detailed deprecation and sunset clauses.\n\n#### Section 7. Error Handling\n\n- **Error Format**: The API returns errors in the format described in Documentation [e.g., JSON object with `code`, `message`, `details` fields].\n- **Retriable Errors**: Client should retry on [429, 500, 502, 503] with exponential backoff.\n- **Non-Retriable Errors**: [400, 401, 403, 404, 422] indicate client-side issues and should not be retried without corrective action.\n\n#### Section 8. Support & Incident Notes (optional)\n\n> Support terms and any uptime/service levels are governed by [Support Policy / SLA Exhibit], not this Schedule.\n\n#### Section 9. Order of Precedence\n\nIn the event of conflict between this Schedule and the Documentation:\n\n- **Option A** (provider-friendly): This Schedule controls only where it **expressly** states a commitment; otherwise Documentation controls.\n- **Option B** (customer-friendly): This Schedule controls.\n\n[Select one and delete the other.]\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4: Traceability, Validation & Risk Flags\n\n### Objective\n\nEnsure every exhibit statement is traceable to a technical source and identify items needing engineering or legal confirmation.\n\n### Deliverables\n\n1. **Traceability Matrix**\n2. **Risk/Gap Log**\n\n### Template: Traceability Matrix\n\n| Exhibit Section | Statement / Data Point | Source ID | Spec Path / Anchor | Confidence (H/M/L) | Notes / Needed Confirmation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| \u00a73 | \"60 requests/min per API key\" | S-3 | Rate limits page | M | Confirm by plan/tier |\n| \u00a72 | \"OAuth2 client credentials supported\" | S-1 | components.securitySchemes | H | |\n| \u00a76 | \"30 days' notice for Breaking Changes\" | S-4 | Changelog policy | L | Not in spec; only in blog |\n\n### Template: Risk/Gap Log\n\n| ID | Issue | Impact | Proposed Fix | Owner | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| G-1 | Rate limits not specified in spec; only on marketing page | Potential over-commitment | Reference docs; avoid numeric commitments | Legal/Eng | Open |\n| G-2 | Sensitive fields unclear (DOB present in examples) | Privacy risk | Confirm data classification; update DPA mapping | Privacy | Open |\n| G-3 | Breaking changes policy found only in README, not spec | Enforceability concern | Confirm with PM; add to Documentation definition | Legal/PM | Open |\n| G-4 | Server URL points to us-east-1; no EU endpoint | Data residency gap | Flag for privacy review | Privacy | Open |\n\n### Checklist (Phase 4)\n\n- [ ] Each numeric limit has a source and tier qualifier (if applicable)\n- [ ] Each auth statement matches operation-level security requirements\n- [ ] Identify any \"beta\" / \"experimental\" endpoints and exclude or label\n- [ ] Confirm whether sandbox differs materially from prod\n- [ ] Confirm webhook retry behavior (often not in OpenAPI)\n- [ ] Ensure exhibit doesn't promise availability/performance unless intended\n- [ ] Verify server URLs against data residency requirements\n- [ ] Confirm error-code-to-SLA mapping is consistent with SLA exhibit\n\n---\n\n## Phase 5: Output Refinement (MANDATORY)\n\n### Checkpoint B: Post-Draft Fit Check\n\nDoes the draft match your needs? Choose refinements (reply with letters):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **A** | **Make strictly descriptive** \u2014 Remove any implied commitments; strengthen disclaimers and cross-references. |\n| **B** | **Convert to binding commitments** \u2014 Add measurable rate limits, notice periods, scope guarantees; require tier mapping. |\n| **C** | **Expand privacy/data handling** \u2014 Identify Personal Data fields; add allowed/prohibited data types; cross-link to DPA/security exhibit. See @privacy-and-security-exhibit-builder. |\n| **D** | **Add change management/deprecation terms** \u2014 Sunset headers, minimum notice, backward compatibility. See @contract-change-management-and-versioning. |\n| **E** | **Reformat for customer paper** \u2014 Adjust order of precedence, add stronger remedies, audit rights references. |\n| **F** | **Generate redline-ready clause alternatives** \u2014 Provider-friendly vs. customer-friendly positions side by side. |\n| **G** | **Produce Risk Matrix** \u2014 Compare Client's requested access vs. the API's technical reality with gap analysis and risk ratings. |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 6: Quality-Control Self-Audit (MANDATORY)\n\n### Pre-Publication QC Checklist\n\n- [ ] **Assumptions Used** are listed at top and reflected in the exhibit language\n- [ ] **Open Items / Needed Inputs** are captured and reflected in Risk/Gap Log\n- [ ] All Phase deliverables present: Source Register, Crosswalk, Extraction Table, Data Field Inventory, Exhibit Draft, Traceability Matrix, Risk/Gap Log\n- [ ] No statement inadvertently creates a warranty (unless intended and approved)\n- [ ] Rate limits are tiered/qualified; no un-sourced numbers\n- [ ] Auth methods/scopes align with spec and docs (no \"OAuth\" if only API keys exist)\n- [ ] Data field classifications are clearly labeled as \"likely\" unless confirmed\n- [ ] Exhibit defines \"Documentation\" and locks retrieval date/version\n- [ ] **Version alignment**: Exhibit references a specific API version (e.g., v1.2), not a generic \"current\" version\n- [ ] **Error-code handling**: Provision addresses how HTTP errors (4xx, 5xx) affect SLA calculations\n- [ ] **PII inventory**: All fields identified in schemas are cross-referenced with the DPA\n- [ ] **Jurisdiction/residency**: If `servers.url` points to a specific region, the contract accounts for data residency\n- [ ] **Security alignment**: Authentication method in spec matches legal security requirements\n- [ ] Order of precedence is explicit\n- [ ] Conflicts/ambiguities are flagged with owners in Risk/Gap Log\n- [ ] Beta/experimental endpoints are excluded or labeled\n\n### Professional Disclaimer\n\nThis skill provides a structured approach to extracting technical data for legal exhibit drafting and does not constitute legal advice. Applicability depends on your contract, industry, and jurisdiction. Confirm technical assertions with qualified engineers and obtain legal review by licensed counsel for the governing jurisdiction.\n\n---\n\n## Output Modes\n\n### Mode 1: Full Package (default)\n\nIncludes all deliverables:\n1. Source Register\n2. Technical-to-Legal Crosswalk\n3. API Constraint Extraction Table\n4. Data Field Inventory\n5. Auth & Access Profile + Rate Limit Profile\n6. Draft API Access & Constraints Schedule\n7. Traceability Matrix\n8. Risk/Gap Log\n\n### Mode 2: Quick Reference\n\n**One-page checklist summary** for deal teams or sales:\n- [ ] Identify authoritative spec and lock version/date\n- [ ] Extract security schemes + scopes; map to operations\n- [ ] Locate rate limit source; confirm tiering; avoid unsourced numbers\n- [ ] List in-scope endpoints; exclude beta/experimental\n- [ ] Inventory required request fields + sensitive data fields\n- [ ] Draft exhibit with \"Documentation as of [date]\" and change-control clause\n- [ ] Map HTTP error codes to SLA treatment\n- [ ] Create traceability for each numeric/technical statement\n\n### Mode 3: Checklist Only\n\nThe extraction and QC checklists from Phases 1, 2, 4, and 6 consolidated as a standalone review protocol.\n\n### Mode 4: Risk Matrix\n\nComparison table of Client's Requested Access vs. API's Technical Reality:\n\n| Constraint Area | Client Request / Expectation | API Technical Reality | Gap? | Risk Level | Recommended Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Rate Limit | Unlimited calls | 1,000/min per key | Yes | Medium | Negotiate higher tier or burst allowance |\n| Auth | SSO/SAML | OAuth2 client credentials only | Yes | High | Confirm roadmap; add contractual commitment |\n| Data Residency | EU-only | US-East-1 only | Yes | High | Flag for privacy counsel |\n\n---\n\n## Cross-References (Related Skills)\n\n- @interpret-openapi-spec-for-legal-review \u2014 Dependency for accurate parsing and mapping of OpenAPI specifications\n- @draft-msa-exhibits-and-schedules \u2014 Structuring exhibits and order-of-precedence clauses\n- @privacy-and-security-exhibit-builder \u2014 Mapping data fields to privacy/security obligations and DPA annexes\n- @contract-change-management-and-versioning \u2014 Deprecation/versioning clauses and notice mechanics",
